metadata.name: (un)connected #337
metadata.description:
A playful collection for #fxhashturnsone.

Controls:

metadata.name: Antilepton Factory #25
metadata.description:
A quasi-simulation exploring variations of the antimatter content of a primitive universe,
1 048 576 particles are subjected to the fluctuations of a digital scalar force field.

Each one of the 60 frames per second is a unique generative composition.

(Click ‚Äòopen‚Äô to see fullscreen, use wheel/pinch to zoom micro/macro )

-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a loopless determinist animation, and a 4320x4320 PNG bitmap.
The "cover" iteration featured here by default uses a 10seconds animation cycle, but new mints will have random animation mode cycles lasting between 1 and 60 seconds. 
To enable the "regular perturbation" mode (10s cycles) please see below "URL modifiers".

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 ‚Üí 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration as the animation scales and creates never-before-seen patterns.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL
- Unique generative and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Unlimited duration (no loop) / 6 animations
- 1 second to 1 minute internal algorithm variations

-----
* Controls *

Wheel/pinch : zoom in/out to observe the phenomenon on different scales
Right click + drag : move the observation area
Key "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&scalartemperature=1400" 
displays the animation with another color.
Colors are expressed in terms of blackbody radiation at a given temperature. Here it will be 1400 Kelvin degrees (~1120¬∞C / 2060¬∞F) corresponding to a lightly hotter than red particles. 
Values accepted in the range 800K to 1 000 000K.

"&perturbation=regular"
allows a regular cycle of animations, each animation mode will be active for 10 seconds

-----
@HAL09999 ‚Äì November 2022

metadata.name: Tilemoji #31
metadata.description:
This collection of low resolution generative art is presented using emojis rather than an image, so it can be copied like normal text. You are also welcome to take a screenshot for sharing or printing. Most results are designed to fit in a 280 character tweet, except for rare extra large variants. There are five different generative algorithms possible, each with their own set of parameters. Emojis are rendered using the Twemoji font and may look different in some environments.

Thank you for supporting my work during the first year of fxhash. For me it has been a life changing experience. I am forever grateful for all of the art and friendships we've created. Many of us have met on social media, so I developed this special project with a fun way to display and share. Congrats to artists, collectors, and developers for an amazing year!

This work is part of the fxhash anniversary event (#fxhashturnsone)
All of primary sale proceeds will go to Save Pakistan

Code and Outputs are Copyright 2022 Frank Force

metadata.name: Return to Apophenia #190
metadata.description:
Fxhash turns one!
Revenue from initial sales divided 50% 40% 10% between Savepakistan, Processing Foundation and the artist.

Apophenia was my first project on fxhash. It seemed fitting to return to this concept for my anniversary mint and recreate it anew, employing many of the skills I have learned over the last year.

It has some fun interaction...

Mouse click in the centre of a hexagon to rotate that hexagon.
Hexagons have 1,2,3 or 6 unique rotations.

On the keyboard:
'c' to regenerate the work with the colours of the palette rotated
'r' to recreate the work with re-randomised hexagons
't' to change the edge tiles so that the complete image becomes a seamlessly tiling rectangle
'y' to generate a symmetrical image with the same scale and colour palette - this will use different hexagons from the original image and any further interaction will act on the original image, not the symmetrical pattern, which almost certainly won't tile

keys 2 through 9 to render at increasing resolutions

's' to save a .png of the current canvas

26 palettes with random rotations + 12 unique hexagons + 10 hexagon combinations + lots of scale and layout possibilities = virtual infinity

Created with p5.js

metadata.name: Annum #2721
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

50% of primary sales go to Savepakistan.

metadata.name: September #210
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle ‚Äúlive mode‚Äù. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
---------------
teaboswell 2022

10% of primary sales will be donated to Girls Who Code (https://girlswhocode.com)

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #279
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Letter #56
metadata.description:
This is a letter from the computer to you by asemic writing. Imagine what message is written on it.

The artwork is inspired from Shodo(Êõ∏ÈÅì) that is known as Japanese calligraphy.
Shodo is the way of writing Kanji and Kana characters with a brush in India ink.
It's one of the traditional Japanese arts.

Paper Color and Ink Color combinations has 18 variations.
Aspect Ratio has 5 variations.
Font Size has 3 variations.
Font Weight has 3 variations.
Font Style has 3 variations.
Each character is randomly generated by a mathematical algorithm.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [f] to switch full screen on and off
- Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
- Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 4800 pixel  (wait a minutes)

Create with p5.js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: fx(splash) #232
metadata.description:
To celebrate fx(hash) turning 1 year old I've created this token as a part of the #fxhashturnsone event! It's a playful and colorful token symbolizing the experiences I've had with this platform.


The piece uses shaders to generate it's visuals which means that outputs will vary from device to device, and the preview might not look the exact same as your live view.

For that same reason I do not recommend running this piece on a mobile device as the shaders can be quite heavy and blurry on lower-tier hardware. My recommended way of viewing this token is on a pc.


--

To open the export menu double click the screen. Here you can export in a multitude of resolutions.

--


50% of primary proceeds will be donated to the processing foundation, learn more about them here:
https://processingfoundation.org

Made with opengl shaders and p5js by WootScoot, 2022.

metadata.name: Bound #51
metadata.description:
Our journey consists of events that happen one after the other, and most of the time these are quite linear. The parts we remember and cherish often happen when we change paths. "Bound" is about letting go and being open to events that are unpredictable and thus gaining new colorfull experiences. 

This collection exists of connected rectangles on a tight grid with lines cutting their way through the patterns made with a simple algorithm.

Press s in live mode to download.

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje November 2022

metadata.name: Misunderstanding #66
metadata.description:
Each color/stripe represents a single person or a group of people, trying to communicate with each other. But their attempts in an understandable and agreeable communication are mostly always misaligned. Hence, none of them understand each other as they want to be understood. And for that, some of them don't even bother trying to communicate at all.

* * *

Happy anniversary! #fxhashturnsone

Press S to save as PNG. To save a larger image, open live view, add "&s=WIDTH_IN_PIXELS" to the end of the URL, press Enter and then press S.
